WEBVTT

00:00.841 --> 00:09.329
♪♪

00:09.329 --> 00:17.738
♪♪

00:17.738 --> 00:27.427
♪♪

00:27.427 --> 00:30.150
[ Ting ]

00:30.150 --> 00:32.713
[ Tuning fork resonating ]

00:43.323 --> 00:45.445
[ Resonating continues ]

01:05.506 --> 01:09.710
[ Tuning fork resonating ]

01:09.710 --> 01:11.512
‐I hear it.

01:11.512 --> 01:13.594
[ Resonating continues ]

01:13.594 --> 01:17.798
♪♪

01:17.798 --> 01:20.601
How bad you want this.

01:20.601 --> 01:23.243
[ Wind whistling ]

01:24.925 --> 01:27.207
How bad you need this.

01:27.207 --> 01:30.691
♪♪

01:30.691 --> 01:32.773
How close it is.

01:32.773 --> 01:34.935
[ Tuning fork resonating ]

01:34.935 --> 01:41.742
♪♪

01:41.742 --> 01:44.024
How far away it is.

01:56.236 --> 01:58.799
‐[ Clears throat ]

02:01.922 --> 02:04.044
Dear Madam President...

02:04.044 --> 02:07.768
we the undersigned,
the crew of <i>Providence 2,</i>

02:07.768 --> 02:10.490
remain fully committed
in body and spirit

02:10.490 --> 02:15.616
to carry out our mission despite
the formidable risks we face.

02:15.616 --> 02:17.377
During our years of training,
our families

02:17.377 --> 02:19.620
and the American people
have placed their faith in us.

02:19.620 --> 02:23.303
[ Muffled, distorted ]
We humbly ask that you place
your faith in us, as well

02:23.303 --> 02:27.908
Allow us to fulfill
the destiny of all humankind...

02:27.908 --> 02:30.751
[ Clearly ] ...as we pave
our way to the future.

02:35.075 --> 02:38.198
Thoughts? Objections?

02:38.198 --> 02:39.720
‐You want us to sign now?
‐No.

02:39.720 --> 02:42.563
We can wait and see
how it goes tomorrow.

02:42.563 --> 02:45.445
‐Anything else?

02:45.445 --> 02:48.809
Okay.
Oh nine hundred, work room.

02:48.809 --> 02:54.575
[ Faint ringing ]

02:58.018 --> 03:01.542
‐We'll need to keep this
confidential.

03:01.542 --> 03:03.463
‐Of course.

03:05.586 --> 03:07.788
[ Whirring ]

03:10.951 --> 03:12.873
All right.

03:17.518 --> 03:19.680
Enlarge times two.

03:19.680 --> 03:22.122
[ Beeping ]

03:26.727 --> 03:28.488
Cam off.

03:28.488 --> 03:30.811
[ Whirring ]

03:34.374 --> 03:36.617
‐Oh.

03:39.580 --> 03:41.341
‐Okay.

03:41.341 --> 03:43.143
All right.

03:43.143 --> 03:45.345
‐I've been having sinus issues.

03:45.345 --> 03:47.427
I thought it was just me trying
to equalize in the tank,

03:47.427 --> 03:49.429
but it was the rupture.

03:49.429 --> 03:51.832
‐Mm‐hmm. Um, treatment?

03:51.832 --> 03:55.035
‐0.14 mils of Ciprodex,
twice a day.

04:00.240 --> 04:03.684
‐The retrofitting cost
to resume service launches ‐‐

04:03.684 --> 04:05.485
just for the sake
of making pennies.

04:05.485 --> 04:07.167
That's not something
that we've ‐‐

04:07.167 --> 04:09.249
<i>‐I'll take pennies</i>
<i>over nothing,</i>

04:09.249 --> 04:12.292
<i>unless you want to start</i>
<i>talking outright sale.</i>

04:12.292 --> 04:15.015
<i>‐We need some ideas</i>
<i>about alternative...</i>

04:15.015 --> 04:17.858
‐I will pull together
some financials

04:17.858 --> 04:19.860
and see what
a scale‐back looks like.

04:19.860 --> 04:21.702
<i>‐How soon can you</i>
<i>have that for us?</i>

04:21.702 --> 04:24.104
‐I could probably have
a rough draft ready by tomorrow

04:24.104 --> 04:25.546
if absolutely necessary.

04:25.546 --> 04:27.347
<i>‐All right.</i>
<i>I'll let everyone know.</i>

04:27.347 --> 04:29.269
‐Okay, thanks. End call.
[ Beep ]

04:29.269 --> 04:30.991
Is everyone willing to sign?

04:30.991 --> 04:34.074
‐Everyone has spoken
to their loved ones.

04:35.155 --> 04:37.477
‐Good. Hopefully,
we won't have to use it.

04:37.477 --> 04:39.840
Come on. I'll walk you out.

04:42.723 --> 04:44.685
‐Trouble with the board?
‐Oh, yeah.

04:44.685 --> 04:47.888
Uh, tell Rosen to pull up
the full asset portfolio.

04:47.888 --> 04:49.850
I‐I'll ‐‐
I'll see him in a minute.

04:49.850 --> 04:52.813
Um, I had to fight off a mutiny
after the first mission,

04:52.813 --> 04:56.296
and I can feel
another one brewing.

04:56.296 --> 04:59.099
How about you? Have you
spoken to who you need to?

04:59.099 --> 05:02.583
‐I've written her several times,
but she hasn't responded.

05:02.583 --> 05:04.184
‐Huh.
‐Has she said anything to you?

05:04.184 --> 05:08.428
‐No. She keeps to herself.

05:08.428 --> 05:11.512
‐Well, if she's wearing out
her welcome, you know...

05:11.512 --> 05:13.634
‐Of course not.
You know I'd say if she was.

05:16.677 --> 05:19.520
Maybe you should do more
than write.

05:19.520 --> 05:22.442
Come and visit.
It's an open invitation.

05:23.684 --> 05:25.926
‐Thank you. I appreciate it.

05:27.247 --> 05:31.211
[ Rhythmic tapping ]

05:31.211 --> 05:34.655
‐Yeah. N‐No.
We don't need to rush anything.

05:34.655 --> 05:36.537
If it is just two hours,
then that's fine.

05:36.537 --> 05:38.378
But if it's any more,
then I really think

05:38.378 --> 05:41.822
we should consider ‐‐
No. Okay.

05:41.822 --> 05:43.383
Is that a three‐three‐two?

05:43.383 --> 05:44.625
‐Uh, yeah.
I'm doing additive meters.

05:44.625 --> 05:46.226
‐That's very good.

05:46.226 --> 05:49.069
Jason, are you on?
Not on the table.

05:49.069 --> 05:50.951
No, no, it's just my son.

05:50.951 --> 05:54.074
Um, so, yeah, we should get
Samantha onto this.

05:54.074 --> 05:56.597
Tell the press there'll be
a two‐hour delay

05:56.597 --> 05:59.159
for a minor course correction
on the rover.

05:59.159 --> 06:01.762
Eitan, you give her
the language, okay?

06:01.762 --> 06:03.604
I'll be out of pocket
for half an hour,

06:03.604 --> 06:05.285
and, uh, then
I'll check back in.

06:05.285 --> 06:08.008
Okay. End call. Phone off.

06:08.008 --> 06:11.131
Hello. Nicole.
This is lovely. Thank you.

06:11.131 --> 06:13.614
Um, I hope you haven't
stopped playing the piano.

06:13.614 --> 06:15.536
I haven't heard you practice.

06:15.536 --> 06:18.098
‐Your piano's out of tune.
‐I‐Is it?

06:18.098 --> 06:22.022
Well, I'll get the piano tuner
to come tomorrow, then.

06:22.022 --> 06:25.105
Amanda?!
‐She's not here.

06:25.105 --> 06:27.908
‐Where is she?

06:27.908 --> 06:29.910
[ Insects chirping ]

06:34.715 --> 06:36.156
[ Laughter ]

06:36.156 --> 06:38.118
‐Thank you. [ Laughs ]

06:39.319 --> 06:43.524
‐Hey. It's dinner.

06:43.524 --> 06:46.206
‐Look.
Denise is teaching me.

06:46.206 --> 06:49.650
‐That's really good.

06:49.650 --> 06:50.971
‐Can she eat with us?

06:50.971 --> 06:53.493
‐No. No, no, no.
I'm not hungry.

06:53.493 --> 06:56.056
‐You don't have to eat, then.
You can just sit with us.

06:56.056 --> 06:59.339
‐Amanda, it's your family time.
‐So?

06:59.339 --> 07:01.582
‐Uh, let her be.
She said she's not hungry.

07:01.582 --> 07:04.424
Come on.
Dinner will get cold otherwise.

07:13.313 --> 07:16.797
I know you have good intentions,
but I'd prefer if ‐‐

07:16.797 --> 07:18.959
‐I know, I know.
I'm really ‐‐ I'm sorry.

07:18.959 --> 07:23.363
‐No need to apologize.
Just some boundaries.

07:23.363 --> 07:26.727
I don't get much time with them
when they're here, so...

07:26.727 --> 07:28.248
‐Yeah. I get it.

07:28.248 --> 07:30.490
‐Thank you.
‐Yeah.

07:30.490 --> 07:35.816
Hey, I don't ‐‐ I don't know
if she wants this, but here.

07:35.816 --> 07:38.579
She's got a great hand.

07:38.579 --> 07:40.380
‐[ Chuckles ]

07:40.380 --> 07:45.225
‐So, your dad mentioned that
he'd been trying to reach out.

07:45.225 --> 07:47.187
Um...

07:49.630 --> 07:51.672
You might want to consider
writing back.

07:56.476 --> 07:58.278
Have a good night.

07:58.278 --> 08:00.521
[ Door closes ]

08:23.183 --> 08:25.986
[ Classical music plays ]

08:25.986 --> 08:33.353
♪♪

08:33.353 --> 08:40.801
♪♪

08:40.801 --> 08:48.168
♪♪

08:48.168 --> 08:55.576
♪♪

08:55.576 --> 09:02.983
♪♪

09:02.983 --> 09:10.350
♪♪

09:10.350 --> 09:17.798
♪♪

09:17.798 --> 09:25.165
♪♪

09:25.165 --> 09:27.247
[ Music continues faintly ]

09:27.247 --> 09:33.413
♪♪

09:33.413 --> 09:39.620
♪♪

09:39.620 --> 09:46.667
♪♪

09:46.667 --> 09:49.910
[ Bottles rattle ]

09:49.910 --> 09:52.072
[ Refrigerator door closes ]

09:55.075 --> 09:57.397
‐Where'd you go?!
‐I'll be right back.

09:57.397 --> 09:59.119
[ Bottle cap rattles ]

10:01.922 --> 10:03.844
Hey.

10:03.844 --> 10:06.206
‐Hey.

10:06.206 --> 10:08.168
‐Are you worried
about tomorrow?

10:10.250 --> 10:14.094
‐Oh. Can't worry about things
that you can't control.

10:14.094 --> 10:16.136
‐[ Chuckles softly ]

10:16.136 --> 10:18.098
Do you think it'll work?

10:18.098 --> 10:19.940
‐It's a fix that's
never been tried before,

10:19.940 --> 10:23.544
but if it doesn't work,
our odds are not so good

10:23.544 --> 10:26.066
about getting back.

10:26.066 --> 10:29.710
‐How much?

10:29.710 --> 10:33.273
‐One in five
that we get stuck there.

10:33.273 --> 10:35.956
‐Jesus.
‐Yeah.

10:38.559 --> 10:41.201
Would you have let Mattie go
with those odds?

10:43.644 --> 10:46.446
‐Mattie would've made up
his own mind regardless.

10:46.446 --> 10:49.289
‐But what would you
have said to him?

10:52.853 --> 10:57.377
‐We're friends, Tom.
Good friends.

10:57.377 --> 11:00.541
But I'm not your wife.

11:00.541 --> 11:03.984
And I'm not your daughter.

11:03.984 --> 11:07.147
She's the one
you should be asking, not me.

11:09.029 --> 11:11.792
‐I've written her.
‐And?

11:11.792 --> 11:13.313
‐Nothing.

11:13.313 --> 11:15.916
‐Still?
‐Yeah.

11:33.734 --> 11:36.737
[ Press corps
shouting questions ]

11:44.184 --> 11:47.227
<i>‐Rover primary systems nominal.</i>

11:47.227 --> 11:49.870
[ Indistinct conversations ]

11:52.112 --> 11:53.994
<i>We can expect</i>
<i>a brief signal drop‐off</i>

11:53.994 --> 11:57.197
<i>as we switch to rover</i>
<i>and HAB camera feeds.</i>

11:57.197 --> 11:59.880
‐Good morning.

11:59.880 --> 12:02.042
Morning.

12:02.042 --> 12:06.807
<i>‐Standing by for rover</i>
<i>guidance initiation.</i>

12:09.409 --> 12:12.172
<i>‐The Mars Ascent Vehicle</i>
<i>known as the MAV</i>

12:12.172 --> 12:15.375
<i>has been on the Martian surface</i>
<i>for nearly four years.</i>

12:15.375 --> 12:17.417
<i>Its purpose is to</i>
<i>return the astronauts</i>

12:17.417 --> 12:19.339
<i>to their orbiting</i>
<i>transit vehicle...</i>

12:19.339 --> 12:21.221
‐Hi.
‐Hey.

12:21.221 --> 12:24.304
Aren't you supposed to
be in school?

12:24.304 --> 12:26.266
‐I told Mom I was sick.

12:26.266 --> 12:27.868
<i>‐...fix the malfunction</i>

12:27.868 --> 12:29.990
<i>by using a survey rover</i>
<i>to short‐circuit ‐‐</i>

12:29.990 --> 12:31.552
‐Are you watching?
‐Yeah.

12:31.552 --> 12:33.754
<i>‐...and reboot</i>
<i>its computer system.</i>

12:33.754 --> 12:35.315
‐You should come watch
at our house.

12:35.315 --> 12:37.077
The screen is way bigger.
‐[ Chuckles ]

12:37.077 --> 12:39.319
<i>‐We can see the power line</i>
<i>and the...</i>

12:39.319 --> 12:42.362
‐Yeah, your mom doesn't
really want us spending ‐‐

12:42.362 --> 12:43.844
‐She's not here.

12:43.844 --> 12:45.205
<i>‐The footage</i>
<i>you're seeing is a....</i>

12:45.205 --> 12:46.927
[ Tuning fork resonates ]

12:46.927 --> 12:49.810
[ Piano note plays ]

12:51.211 --> 12:53.694
[ Piano note playing ]

12:53.694 --> 12:55.055
‐Screen on!

12:55.055 --> 12:58.058
[ TV Channels cycling ]

12:58.058 --> 13:00.621
<i>‐The command would have reached</i>
<i>the rover several minutes ago.</i>

13:00.621 --> 13:02.102
<i>We're just moments away</i>

13:02.102 --> 13:04.024
<i>from seeing the footage</i>
<i>of the result.</i>

13:04.024 --> 13:07.107
<i>Kathy, what's the feeling like</i>
<i>there in Mission Control?</i>

13:07.107 --> 13:09.950
<i>‐Everyone's eyes are glued to</i>
<i>the big screens up front here.</i>

13:09.950 --> 13:11.351
<i>You can feel the anxiousness</i>

13:11.351 --> 13:13.794
<i>and anticipation</i>
<i>in the viewing area.</i>

13:13.794 --> 13:16.797
<i>There's a lot riding on this ‐‐</i>
<i>months of work and testing,</i>

13:16.797 --> 13:18.599
<i>hundreds of engineers</i>
<i>and support staff</i>

13:18.599 --> 13:21.001
<i>working around the clock</i>
<i>because the future</i>

13:21.001 --> 13:23.804
<i>of the</i> Providence 2 <i>mission</i>
<i>is on the line.</i>

13:23.804 --> 13:26.486
<i>‐Drill spin initiated.</i>

13:30.811 --> 13:34.655
‐Drill at speed.

13:34.655 --> 13:39.740
Drill lowering
in three, two, one.

13:39.740 --> 13:43.383
<i>‐Stand by for</i>
<i>intermediate contact.</i>

13:48.909 --> 13:51.592
‐Contact with the cord.

13:53.674 --> 13:58.158
Penetration in three, two, one.

14:01.522 --> 14:04.525
<i>‐Drill‐bit</i>
<i>vaporization confirmed.</i>

14:04.525 --> 14:07.848
<i>Stand by for</i>
<i>MAV systems reboot.</i>

14:16.336 --> 14:19.419
[ Onlookers murmuring ]

14:19.419 --> 14:22.422
<i>‐We have a signal.</i>
<i>Reboot initiating.</i>

14:22.422 --> 14:25.506
[ Cheers and applause ]

14:30.951 --> 14:33.113
‐That's the magic.

14:33.113 --> 14:34.314
‐The same.

14:35.756 --> 14:38.679
Stop! Stop!

14:38.679 --> 14:40.921
[ Applause stops ]

14:42.883 --> 14:45.165
Show me all the sensor data.
‐W‐What's going on?

14:45.165 --> 14:48.048
[ Keys clacking, beeping ]

14:48.048 --> 14:51.572
‐It's the same as before.
LOX levels and sensors.

14:51.572 --> 14:56.496
♪♪

14:56.496 --> 15:02.102
♪♪

15:02.102 --> 15:04.545
Clear the room, please.
‐Essential personnel only.

15:04.545 --> 15:06.547
Everyone else please exit
the control room.

15:06.547 --> 15:08.268
‐Oh, boy.

15:08.268 --> 15:11.271
[ Indistinct conversations ]

15:11.271 --> 15:17.397
♪♪

15:17.397 --> 15:19.760
All right. Let's let them
have the room. Come on.

15:19.760 --> 15:21.842
Come on. Let's go.

15:24.965 --> 15:29.610
[ Door opens and closes ]

15:29.610 --> 15:32.813
<i>‐...briefly came back online</i>
<i>before they lost contact again.</i>

15:32.813 --> 15:35.255
<i>Kathy, any new developments</i>
<i>on your end?</i>

15:35.255 --> 15:37.177
<i>‐They've asked all the media</i>
<i>and invited guests</i>

15:37.177 --> 15:39.099
<i>to exit Mission Control.</i>

15:39.099 --> 15:42.422
<i>No one from VISTA or NASA</i>
<i>had officially briefed us yet,</i>

15:42.422 --> 15:43.944
<i>but a few people</i>
<i>I've spoken to have...</i>

15:43.944 --> 15:45.706
‐That was the
worst‐case scenario.

15:45.706 --> 15:47.427
I could have cooked the numbers
to make it more palatable,

15:47.427 --> 15:49.029
but I wanted to be
straight with you.

15:49.029 --> 15:52.152
‐It's more than three times
the approved parameters.

15:52.152 --> 15:53.554
‐Internal NASA guidelines,

15:53.554 --> 15:55.435
not required
by the funding legislation.

15:55.435 --> 15:58.118
Bob is willing to override
with your approval.

15:58.118 --> 16:01.241
‐What if a doctor told you
there was a one‐in‐five chance

16:01.241 --> 16:04.044
you'd die during
elective surgery?

16:04.044 --> 16:07.007
‐The astronauts are electing
to risk their lives.

16:07.007 --> 16:11.331
I have a letter here confirming
their commitment to do so.

16:11.331 --> 16:15.616
‐Well, maybe they're prepared
to take that gamble. I'm not.

16:15.616 --> 16:20.300
‐Imagine the responsibility
the astronauts shoulder ‐‐

16:20.300 --> 16:23.864
the years of training, the toll
it takes on their families,

16:23.864 --> 16:27.347
the personal sacrifices
that they've endured.

16:27.347 --> 16:30.631
And then they strap themselves
to a rocket,

16:30.631 --> 16:35.636
and they risk their lives
in an attempt to accomplish...

16:37.918 --> 16:42.282
...the greatest pioneering feat
in human history.

16:42.282 --> 16:48.008
That's five people fulfilling
the destiny of eight billion.

16:48.008 --> 16:54.094
I'm asking you, as the most
powerful person on this planet,

16:54.094 --> 16:56.897
to help us get to another one.

16:56.897 --> 17:01.502
♪♪

17:01.502 --> 17:05.225
‐One in five.

17:05.225 --> 17:09.109
Yesterday, that was theoretical,

17:09.109 --> 17:12.152
and today it's a reality.

17:12.152 --> 17:16.637
So before you sign this letter,

17:16.637 --> 17:20.320
I want you to take one more
night to reconsider ‐‐

17:20.320 --> 17:23.363
one more night to
talk to your loved ones

17:23.363 --> 17:27.848
and to make sure that your name
belongs on this piece of paper.

17:27.848 --> 17:31.051
I've promised the President
unwavering commitment,

17:31.051 --> 17:34.054
and I need to know
that I'm telling her the truth.

17:37.217 --> 17:40.220
‐Well, in either case,
no later than tomorrow at noon.

17:40.220 --> 17:41.862
We'd like to give you more time,

17:41.862 --> 17:44.825
but the momentum can shift
in D. C.,

17:44.825 --> 17:48.108
and we got to beat that.

17:48.108 --> 17:51.071
‐And you come on your own.

17:51.071 --> 17:55.395
If you choose not to,
no judgment, no questions.

17:57.918 --> 18:02.202
[ Whirring ]

18:02.202 --> 18:04.444
[ Knocking on glass ]

18:04.444 --> 18:08.689
[ Whirring stops ]

18:11.211 --> 18:12.893
‐The board's holding
an emergency meeting ‐‐

18:12.893 --> 18:16.577
contingency plan if
the President doesn't approve.

18:16.577 --> 18:18.779
‐Scale‐down?
‐Yeah.

18:18.779 --> 18:20.701
I mean,
we didn't set out to make

18:20.701 --> 18:24.745
a boutique sat‐launch service
grinding for volume, did we?

18:24.745 --> 18:27.267
‐No. No, we did not.

18:30.751 --> 18:34.795
‐So, you should be
thinking about a plan,

18:34.795 --> 18:36.917
your next step,
if you haven't already.

18:36.917 --> 18:38.799
‐Oh, no.
I'm dusting off my guitar.

18:38.799 --> 18:42.603
‐[ Laughs ] This again?
You don't even play the guitar.

18:42.603 --> 18:44.444
‐Oh, you should hear
my cover of "Kashmir."

18:44.444 --> 18:47.207
‐[ Laughs ] No, I shouldn't.
Anything but Zeppelin.

18:47.207 --> 18:50.210
‐Jimmy Page is a god to me.

18:50.210 --> 18:52.853
‐You sound like my dad.
He used to play "Zeppelin IV"

18:52.853 --> 18:55.976
around the clock
my entire childhood.

18:55.976 --> 18:58.058
‐Good man.

18:58.058 --> 19:00.420
[ Laughs ]

19:00.420 --> 19:04.785
‐I got to say, you, um,
you seem remarkably poised

19:04.785 --> 19:09.229
given that your life's dream
might be going down the toilet.

19:09.229 --> 19:12.833
‐Steady stream of painkillers.
‐Which ones?

19:12.833 --> 19:15.235
‐[ Laughs ]

19:17.518 --> 19:19.760
‐What's the alternative, running
around like a headless chicken?

19:19.760 --> 19:21.602
It doesn't accomplish anything.

19:26.366 --> 19:29.930
It's up to the crew now.
It's in their hands, not ours.

19:38.098 --> 19:41.862
‐You have always been
so supportive of me,

19:41.862 --> 19:44.304
and you've never put up a fight.

19:47.307 --> 19:50.831
It's okay, though.

19:50.831 --> 19:52.993
This is different.

19:55.716 --> 19:57.918
So now's the time.

20:02.322 --> 20:04.284
Oh, sweetie.

20:10.531 --> 20:12.853
‐That handle.

20:14.294 --> 20:16.537
There. You see it?

20:16.537 --> 20:18.819
‐No.

20:18.819 --> 20:21.662
‐The grub screw is loose.
Or the tumbler's not aligned.

20:21.662 --> 20:25.025
It's not level.

20:25.025 --> 20:28.028
We'll have to fix that
before it drives me nuts.

20:33.433 --> 20:36.517
Well, sometimes I look around,

20:36.517 --> 20:39.479
and I think there isn't
one inch of this house

20:39.479 --> 20:40.881
that we didn't build together.

20:40.881 --> 20:43.043
‐[ Chuckles softly ]

20:43.043 --> 20:45.886
Mostly you.

20:45.886 --> 20:48.248
‐It's both of us.

20:49.770 --> 20:51.732
[ Chuckles ]

20:51.732 --> 20:54.294
Okay, yeah, mostly me.
‐[ Chuckles ]

20:57.738 --> 21:01.181
It's gonna be pretty empty
around here.

21:04.424 --> 21:05.986
[ Chuckles ]

21:05.986 --> 21:08.989
‐It's a small price
for changing the world, huh?

21:08.989 --> 21:11.351
‐[ Chuckles ]

21:12.913 --> 21:16.316
‐I love you.
You know that?

21:16.316 --> 21:17.958
So much.

21:25.445 --> 21:27.528
I'll help you fix it.

21:31.051 --> 21:33.453
The handle.
You were gonna fix the handle.

21:33.453 --> 21:34.775
‐Right. The handle.

21:34.775 --> 21:36.136
[ Both chuckle ]

21:36.136 --> 21:38.378
‐Come on.

21:38.378 --> 21:39.900
‐It's, uh, flat‐head.
‐Okay.

21:39.900 --> 21:42.022
‐Flat‐head and a‐a ‐‐
and an Allen wrench.

21:42.022 --> 21:44.064
‐Okay.

21:45.506 --> 21:49.590
Well, you always end up
asking for something else.

21:49.590 --> 21:53.033
Here. It's for you.

22:03.043 --> 22:05.566
‐Fuck.

22:09.449 --> 22:12.092
‐This isn't an
unfair thing to ask.

22:12.092 --> 22:14.454
‐It doesn't feel
like you are asking.

22:14.454 --> 22:17.778
‐I'm gonna be a single father
for two and a half years.

22:17.778 --> 22:19.780
Maybe forever.
‐Don't talk that way.

22:19.780 --> 22:21.622
‐I have to talk this way,

22:21.622 --> 22:23.904
'cause I have to wrap
my brain around it...

22:23.904 --> 22:28.669
which is hard enough.

22:28.669 --> 22:31.832
I can't take care
of your mom and the boys.

22:31.832 --> 22:34.955
It's...way too much.

22:38.278 --> 22:40.801
She's becoming a full‐time job.

22:40.801 --> 22:42.923
‐I'm just ‐‐ I'm scared
for her, all right,

22:42.923 --> 22:44.725
being in a place
full of strangers?

22:44.725 --> 22:49.409
‐And I'm scared shitless
I'm gonna lose my wife...

22:49.409 --> 22:52.292
that the boys
will lose their mother.

22:52.292 --> 22:55.015
[ Boys shouting playfully
in distance ]

22:55.015 --> 22:58.859
She's lived her life.

22:58.859 --> 23:00.380
Theirs is just beginning.

23:00.380 --> 23:03.544
‐Could you keep it down?
She is going to hear you.

23:03.544 --> 23:06.947
‐She's in her own world
right now.

23:06.947 --> 23:08.468
‐Look, if you don't want me

23:08.468 --> 23:10.511
to sign, then you say
that you don't want me ‐‐

23:10.511 --> 23:13.233
‐I'm not asking for that.

23:16.236 --> 23:18.999
I'm asking that you let her go.

23:22.603 --> 23:24.965
If we have to let you go...

23:28.088 --> 23:31.491
...I have to give
all my energy to the boys.

23:47.708 --> 23:49.990
‐Mom.

23:53.473 --> 23:55.355
[ Chair slides ]

23:57.117 --> 23:59.960
Hey, Mom, can I talk to you?

24:04.805 --> 24:07.287
‐I'll make friends.

24:07.287 --> 24:09.730
‐[ Chuckles ]

24:17.658 --> 24:19.259
‐If it weren't you ‐‐
Okay, if it was

24:19.259 --> 24:21.181
one of the others,
wouldn't you say something?

24:21.181 --> 24:23.944
Wouldn't you take action?
‐It's just a second opinion.

24:23.944 --> 24:25.986
‐One that you're
completely ignoring!

24:25.986 --> 24:27.948
‐That is not true.

24:27.948 --> 24:30.190
‐Matteo, you wouldn't
even have told me

24:30.190 --> 24:33.554
if I didn't ask you
like 20 times.

24:33.554 --> 24:35.475
‐I know what I'm doing.
‐Okay.

24:35.475 --> 24:37.518
I think you're being foolish.

24:37.518 --> 24:40.240
You're being reckless
and dishonest!

24:40.240 --> 24:42.322
‐Lay the fuck off me!

24:42.322 --> 24:44.765
I am making a judgment call.
I went to school for this.

24:44.765 --> 24:46.927
I trained half my life for this,
and that is why

24:46.927 --> 24:50.210
they are putting it on me
to make these evaluations!

24:52.132 --> 24:55.415
‐Yeah. Except you're giving
yourself special treatment.

24:55.415 --> 24:57.297
‐[ Scoffs ] Special ‐‐
You know what? Just ‐‐

24:57.297 --> 24:59.019
You don't know what
you're talking about.

24:59.019 --> 25:01.702
‐I get it. You think that

25:01.702 --> 25:05.105
I'm just using this
to keep you here.

25:05.105 --> 25:07.427
‐I don't know. Are you?

25:09.910 --> 25:11.912
‐Maybe that's part of it.

25:11.912 --> 25:13.514
[ Siren wails in distance ]

25:13.514 --> 25:15.195
I don't know.

25:15.195 --> 25:16.957
‐Well, I don't expect you
to wait for me,

25:16.957 --> 25:19.800
so if you need to move on,
if we need to end this now ‐‐

25:19.800 --> 25:21.882
‐Asshole.

25:23.163 --> 25:26.727
‐I'm just saying
this isn't fair to you,

25:26.727 --> 25:28.408
to ask that.

25:28.408 --> 25:30.651
‐Matteo.

25:35.255 --> 25:38.899
I...love you.

25:38.899 --> 25:43.343
Okay? I ‐‐ I'd wait.

25:43.343 --> 25:46.867
And would I rather you stay?
Yes.

25:50.030 --> 25:52.352
‐I'm going.

26:32.392 --> 26:35.435
‐Oh, my God. What are we doing?
‐I don't know.

26:35.435 --> 26:37.998
‐[ Both laugh ]

26:40.761 --> 26:43.083
‐How your boys handling it?

26:43.083 --> 26:46.246
‐Well, it won't easy,
but, uh, they have Todd.

26:46.246 --> 26:50.210
‐Your mom?
‐Not as great.

26:50.210 --> 26:52.653
‐I'm sorry to hear that.

26:52.653 --> 26:54.294
‐What about you?

26:54.294 --> 26:55.776
‐My mom's a prick.

26:55.776 --> 26:59.179
‐[ Laughs ]
‐And my dad's a bigger prick,

26:59.179 --> 27:02.382
Got no girl.
No time for friends.

27:02.382 --> 27:06.987
So you guys
are pretty much my family.

27:09.630 --> 27:12.352
So I didn't lose
a lot of sleep last night.

27:15.876 --> 27:18.799
Fuck it. Let's go to Mars!
‐[ Chuckles ] Okay.

27:18.799 --> 27:20.801
[ Both laugh ]

27:20.801 --> 27:23.083
[ Indistinct conversations ]

27:29.449 --> 27:31.572
[ Laughter ]

28:15.335 --> 28:19.900
[ Faint ringing ]

28:54.735 --> 28:57.377
‐How long have you
known about this?

28:57.377 --> 28:59.900
‐It happened when you
flew me out to Houston,

28:59.900 --> 29:02.903
the day Tom had to
leave early ‐‐

29:02.903 --> 29:05.385
the pressure in the tank.

29:05.385 --> 29:08.589
‐So, um, why didn't you
say anything then?

29:08.589 --> 29:10.951
‐I didn't think
it was a big deal.

29:10.951 --> 29:13.313
It should have healed on its own
after a few weeks.

29:13.313 --> 29:16.276
Problem is,
it keeps getting infected,

29:16.276 --> 29:18.799
probably because
it's happened before.

29:18.799 --> 29:22.162
The scar tissue
slows the healing process.

29:24.084 --> 29:26.366
The messed‐up part is
I probably wouldn't be here

29:26.366 --> 29:28.368
if it hadn't been for the...

29:28.368 --> 29:30.531
[ Gunfire ]

29:30.531 --> 29:34.254
Syria.
It was my second tour.

29:34.254 --> 29:37.017
We were ambushed.

29:37.017 --> 29:39.499
I'm lying there.

29:39.499 --> 29:45.425
All I can hear is this ringing,
like a drill going into my head.

29:45.425 --> 29:47.908
[ Faint ringing ]

29:47.908 --> 29:51.672
♪♪

29:51.672 --> 29:54.955
I knew right away
it was my eardrum.

29:58.358 --> 30:00.561
I see the tracers.

30:03.644 --> 30:05.886
Then I see the stars.

30:08.288 --> 30:11.652
They're perfect.

30:11.652 --> 30:15.295
They're filling up the sky
like they're protecting me,

30:15.295 --> 30:17.938
like they're telling me
that I'll be okay.

30:17.938 --> 30:20.140
[ Gunfire continues ]

30:20.140 --> 30:21.942
The pain went away.

30:21.942 --> 30:24.304
I wasn't afraid of dying.

30:24.304 --> 30:27.828
And that's when I knew ‐‐
where I wanted to be,

30:27.828 --> 30:30.511
what I wanted to do
with the rest of my life.

30:33.834 --> 30:35.916
I guess this is the flip side.

30:45.005 --> 30:47.568
‐We have a decision to make.

30:47.568 --> 30:49.530
‐I've already made it.

30:54.054 --> 30:57.337
I have to hold myself
to the same standard

30:57.337 --> 30:59.540
as any other crew member.

31:02.022 --> 31:04.224
You have to cut me.

31:18.799 --> 31:20.801
‐I was practically on my knees
to the President,

31:20.801 --> 31:22.442
and we have a crew issue?

31:22.442 --> 31:24.965
‐He thought it would
work itself through.

31:24.965 --> 31:27.688
‐A‐And what happens if there's
a medical emergency?

31:27.688 --> 31:30.210
‐Well, Matteo's confident
in our triage training.

31:30.210 --> 31:33.694
Between that
and the on‐board tech,

31:33.694 --> 31:37.658
we have enough redundancies
in place.

31:37.658 --> 31:40.500
‐Okay, so, what next, we just
fast‐track another doctor?

31:40.500 --> 31:43.103
‐No.

31:43.103 --> 31:46.386
‐Sadie.
‐Tom and I discussed this.

31:46.386 --> 31:49.189
If we introduce a brand‐new
element so close to the launch,

31:49.189 --> 31:52.472
there's no telling how
it could have an impact
on the team dynamic.

31:52.472 --> 31:54.154
‐We need to
inform the crew of this.

31:54.154 --> 31:56.036
It may change their decision.

31:56.036 --> 31:58.599
‐It won't.
‐How do you know?

31:58.599 --> 32:01.121
‐Trust me.

32:01.121 --> 32:03.844
Trust me on this.

32:03.844 --> 32:07.848
You've got that thing.

32:07.848 --> 32:09.449
You'll make it.

32:09.449 --> 32:13.373
♪♪

32:13.373 --> 32:15.415
I promise you.

32:15.415 --> 32:23.183
♪♪

32:23.183 --> 32:30.871
♪♪

32:30.871 --> 32:38.639
♪♪

32:38.639 --> 32:47.487
♪♪

32:47.487 --> 32:55.215
♪♪

32:55.215 --> 33:02.983
♪♪

33:02.983 --> 33:05.666
[ Indistinct arguing ]

33:05.666 --> 33:09.510
♪♪

33:09.510 --> 33:12.633
‐They need to show
something to the President
sooner later than later.

33:12.633 --> 33:14.835
‐So sign it.

33:14.835 --> 33:17.998
‐We can talk about it more.

33:17.998 --> 33:21.001
‐With her sitting out there?
‐I'll tell her to go.

33:22.643 --> 33:25.526
‐I can't do this right now.

33:27.127 --> 33:29.329
I feel whipsawed.

33:31.451 --> 33:33.413
It took so long
to get used to you going,

33:33.413 --> 33:34.695
and then you weren't, and now ‐‐

33:34.695 --> 33:36.376
‐But you knew
I was an alternate.

33:36.376 --> 33:38.298
‐So why are you even asking?

33:38.298 --> 33:39.700
‐Because you're my husband,
and I ‐‐

33:39.700 --> 33:42.142
‐And how am I even
supposed to process this?

33:42.142 --> 33:43.904
How do you expect me to ‐‐
‐Ollie.

33:43.904 --> 33:46.426
‐No. I can't do this.

33:49.870 --> 33:53.153
We can talk tomorrow. Or not.

33:53.153 --> 33:55.075
You can do whatever the fuck
you're gonna do, but I can't ‐‐

33:55.075 --> 33:57.237
I can't just put
a brave face on it

33:57.237 --> 34:00.641
and say to you,
"Go. You have my blessing."

34:02.523 --> 34:04.965
Not that it really matters,
does it?

34:08.208 --> 34:13.373
Does it matter, truly,
what I think?

34:13.373 --> 34:17.337
‐I'll never have the opportunity
to do work this important.

34:17.337 --> 34:20.581
I can't pass that up.

34:20.581 --> 34:23.864
I need this.

34:23.864 --> 34:26.547
That hasn't changed.

34:26.547 --> 34:28.428
‐Yeah.

34:28.428 --> 34:31.231
‐Ollie.

34:31.231 --> 34:33.674
Ollie.

34:33.674 --> 34:36.356
[ Footsteps depart ]

34:36.356 --> 34:38.839
[ Piano music plays ]

34:38.839 --> 34:47.848
♪♪

34:47.848 --> 34:55.696
♪♪

34:55.696 --> 35:04.705
♪♪

35:04.705 --> 35:07.147
[ Music stops ]

35:07.147 --> 35:08.989
‐Oh, hey.

35:08.989 --> 35:11.992
I'll ‐‐ I'll go get her.

35:11.992 --> 35:14.234
Mom!

35:42.783 --> 35:46.186
‐Hey, Tom.

35:46.186 --> 35:48.629
‐Nice.
‐[ Chuckles ]

36:10.330 --> 36:13.053
‐Does she know that I'm here?
‐Yeah.

36:15.495 --> 36:17.858
She's ‐‐ She's out there,
to the left.

36:33.393 --> 36:38.959
♪♪

36:38.959 --> 36:45.405
♪♪

36:45.405 --> 36:48.448
[ Knock on door ]

36:54.775 --> 36:59.299
‐Denise? It's Dad!

36:59.299 --> 37:03.223
If you can hear me,
I'm just gonna wait out here.

37:03.223 --> 37:11.512
♪♪

37:11.512 --> 37:19.800
♪♪

37:19.800 --> 37:28.048
♪♪

37:28.048 --> 37:36.376
♪♪

37:36.376 --> 37:45.826
♪♪

37:45.826 --> 37:54.114
♪♪

37:54.114 --> 38:03.604
♪♪

38:15.536 --> 38:18.819
I don't know if you've been
following the news.

38:18.819 --> 38:20.941
‐Yeah. Yeah, I saw.

38:20.941 --> 38:24.224
‐So, I drafted a letter

38:24.224 --> 38:26.947
for the crew to sign
and send to the President.

38:26.947 --> 38:28.909
‐She told me.

38:31.151 --> 38:32.953
‐Yeah.

38:34.354 --> 38:37.157
They've all signed it.

38:41.161 --> 38:43.403
I haven't signed it yet.

38:47.648 --> 38:49.850
‐We can make it work.

38:53.333 --> 38:57.377
No, that's what you told me.

38:57.377 --> 38:59.660
Remember that night
you got back from D. C.?

39:01.622 --> 39:04.424
You'd already decided.

39:04.424 --> 39:06.106
‐I thought that we could.

39:06.106 --> 39:10.270
‐Yeah, so did I.
We were wrong, huh?

39:13.834 --> 39:16.436
‐[ Breathes deeply ]

39:21.161 --> 39:23.163
Did you read any of my e‐mails?

39:23.163 --> 39:25.485
‐Yeah.

39:25.485 --> 39:27.608
There's so many times I wrote
back to you in my head,

39:27.608 --> 39:29.930
but I just ‐‐
I‐I kept coming up

39:29.930 --> 39:32.452
with the same thing ‐‐

39:32.452 --> 39:36.697
"I need you here.
I don't want you to go."

39:42.062 --> 39:45.746
‐Well, if you need me h‐‐
‐Oh, God, no. I ‐‐

39:45.746 --> 39:50.230
I just needed to say that.
So I can stop needing you.

39:53.473 --> 39:55.996
‐I don't think
you do need me, Denise.

39:59.159 --> 40:02.723
They do.
The mission does.

40:02.723 --> 40:05.485
‐Okay, so go!

40:05.485 --> 40:07.688
No one's stopping you.
I'm not stopping you.

40:07.688 --> 40:11.532
But once you go, you're gone.

40:11.532 --> 40:12.933
You're gone.

40:12.933 --> 40:16.056
No texts, no e‐mails.

40:16.056 --> 40:17.978
Nothing.

40:17.978 --> 40:19.580
‐Please don't punish me.

40:19.580 --> 40:22.342
‐No. I'm not punishing you.

40:23.744 --> 40:26.507
I'm protecting myself.

40:29.069 --> 40:33.433
Do you remember what
you told me about Mom?

40:33.433 --> 40:37.077
We have to move on to survive?

40:37.077 --> 40:39.600
Now I have to
move past you, too.

40:39.600 --> 40:42.282
I need distance.

40:48.929 --> 40:52.492
‐This is who I am.

40:52.492 --> 40:54.655
This is who I've always been.

40:54.655 --> 40:56.336
‐Yeah.

40:56.336 --> 41:00.741
You are the choices you make,
and you've made yours.

41:00.741 --> 41:03.143
And I'm making mine.

41:05.465 --> 41:08.549
‐Well, if that's what you need.
‐Yeah, it is.

41:11.151 --> 41:14.595
‐I respect that...

41:14.595 --> 41:16.637
as much as it breaks my heart.

41:16.637 --> 41:18.599
‐Yeah.

41:18.599 --> 41:20.841
Hearts get broken, right?

41:32.292 --> 41:36.777
‐Can we just...
Will you please sit, so we can

41:36.777 --> 41:38.739
just sit together a little
while before I leave?

41:38.739 --> 41:41.301
‐No, Dad, we can't. No.

41:48.268 --> 41:50.991
If you don't walk away, I will.

